<h3>Multi-Currency and International Statements</h3>
<p>International banking creates translation complexity. Indian statements mix Hindi and English with bank-specific abbreviations. UK statements use different date formats (DD/MM/YYYY vs MM/DD/YYYY). US statements include multiple account types in consolidated views. International banks issue multi-currency statements with exchange rate notations that must be accurately rendered.</p>

<p>Every element requires attention: account holder name and address (must match passport exactly), account numbers and IBAN, statement period coverage, all transaction descriptions and amounts, opening and closing balances per currency, and exchange rates where applicable. Immigration authorities verify these details against your application data.</p>

<p>Digital banking exports (PDF downloads from online banking) are strongly preferred—clearer than photographed paper statements and containing all required metadata. We verify that your statement period covers the required months before translation begins.</p>

<div class="hero-highlight-box">
<h4>Immediate Checklist for Bank Statement Translation</h4>
<ul>
<li>6-month consecutive statement coverage</li>
<li>Account holder name matches passport exactly</li>
<li>Balance meets visa category threshold</li>
<li>PDF export from online banking (preferred)</li>
<li>All pages included if multi-page statement</li>
<li>Currency clearly indicated for each balance</li>
